\section*{Discussion}

The simulations conducted using the ToR-ORd dynamic chloride epicardial cell model under paced conditions at a cycle length of 2000 ms revealed profound concentration-dependent alterations in cardiac electrophysiology induced by quinidine, consistent with its known multi-channel blocking profile, particularly hERG/IKr inhibition. In control conditions (0 nM), time-series traces (e.g., Figure 1) displayed characteristic action potential morphology with APD90 around 300 ms, stable repolarization, and baseline calcium transients, while higher concentrations (e.g., 12948 nM, Figure 11) showed markedly prolonged APD90 exceeding 500 ms, elevated peak membrane potential, and slowed calcium transient decay, as evidenced by representative beats where Vm rest hyperpolarized slightly and dVmdt max repolarization decelerated. These beat-level observations were corroborated by ionic current traces, where IKr was progressively reduced across concentrations, alongside modest INaL and ICaL suppression, leading to diminished repolarization reserve and enhanced early afterdepolarizations in high-dose simulations. Calcium handling exhibited delayed CaTD90 and increased peak Cai, reflecting impaired sarcoplasmic reticulum uptake under drug exposure, which aligns with the observed morphological changes in Vm and intracellular dynamics.

Feature-level summary statistics from median and 95\% confidence intervals across stochastic samples further reinforced these trends, with qNet medians shifting positively (e.g., 0.0192 uA/uF at high concentration, Figure 13) indicating net charge accumulation during prolonged plateaus, and qInward distributions broadening (median 0.8245 uA/uF) due to sustained inward currents from reduced outward IKr and IKs. Action potential duration metrics showed APD90 medians rising to 524 ms (CI 494-555 ms) and APD50 to 460 ms (CI 431-488 ms), with triangulation (APDTri median 64.5 ms) highlighting repolarization slowing, while CaTD90 (475 ms, CI 434-488 ms) and CaTD50 (150 ms) exhibited parallel prolongation and increased CaTDTri, suggesting coupled excitation-contraction disruptions. These aggregated distributions nuanced single-beat observations by revealing variability in failure rates (e.g., 96.67\% depolarization failure at 12948 nM), where confidence intervals widened at higher doses, indicating population-level proarrhythmic instability. Within a CiPA-style in silico framework, these patterns—qNet/qInward shifts, APD/CaTD prolongation, and triangulation—support high TdP risk classification for quinidine, as they mechanistically link IKr block to repolarization reserve loss, consistent with empirical expectations, though discrepancies in absolute APD values underscore model-specific sensitivities to parameter variability.
